Database Design for Banking (30 min)

Goal: Design a safe, scalable, normalized banking database

1️⃣ Core Tables (Production Level)
1. USERS

Stores customer info.

USERS
------
user_id        BIGINT  (PK)
name           VARCHAR
email          VARCHAR (UNIQUE)
kyc_verified   BOOLEAN
created_at     TIMESTAMP

Why?

One user can have multiple accounts

KYC required for banking compliance

2. ACCOUNTS

Stores bank account details.

ACCOUNTS
--------
account_id     BIGINT (PK)
user_id        BIGINT (FK → USERS.user_id)
balance        DECIMAL(19,2)
status         VARCHAR (ACTIVE/BLOCKED)
created_at     TIMESTAMP

Why?

One user → Many accounts

Balance stored here (single source of truth)

3. TRANSACTIONS

Stores money movement.

TRANSACTIONS
------------
txn_id         BIGINT (PK)
from_account   BIGINT
to_account     BIGINT
amount         DECIMAL(19,2)
type           VARCHAR (DEBIT/CREDIT/TRANSFER)
status         VARCHAR (SUCCESS/FAILED/PENDING)
reference_id   VARCHAR
created_at     TIMESTAMP

Why?

Every money change must be recorded

Needed for audit + rollback + fraud detection

2️⃣ Relationships (Very Important)
USER 1 ────────< MANY ACCOUNTS

ACCOUNT 1 ─────< MANY TRANSACTIONS

3️⃣ Normalization (Avoid Data Problems)
❌ Wrong (Denormalized)
Account table storing user name, email, phone repeatedly

✅ Correct

User info in USERS table

Account only stores user_id

Benefits:

No duplicate data

Easy updates

Less storage

Data consistency

4️⃣ Indexing (Performance Booster 🚀)

Without index → full table scan → slow queries

Add indexes on:
CREATE INDEX idx_accounts_user ON accounts(user_id);

CREATE INDEX idx_txn_from_account ON transactions(from_account);

CREATE INDEX idx_txn_created_at ON transactions(created_at);


Why?

Find accounts by user → fast

Find transactions by account → fast

Statement history → fast

5️⃣ Data Integrity Rules (Must for Banking)
Constraints
balance >= 0
user must exist before account
account must exist before transaction
amount > 0

Enforced using:

Foreign Keys

NOT NULL

CHECK constraints

Application validation

6️⃣ Ledger vs Balance (Real Banking Concept)
Approach 1 — Store Balance (Simple)

Balance column updated on every txn

Fast reads

Used in most systems

Approach 2 — Ledger Only (Advanced)

Never store balance

Calculate from all transactions

Fully auditable but slower

Real banks → Hybrid (Balance + Ledger)

