📘 ACID Properties (25 min)

ACID ensures money is always safe and correct in database transactions.

Every bank operation (transfer, withdraw, deposit) MUST follow ACID.

A — Atomicity (All or Nothing)
Meaning

A transaction must fully complete OR fully fail — no partial updates.

Banking Example

Transfer ₹1000 from A → B

Steps:

Deduct from A

Add to B

Save transaction record

If step 2 fails → step 1 must rollback.

Without Atomicity ❌

A loses money, B does not receive → data corruption

With Atomicity ✅

Either:

Both succeed ✔️

OR nothing happens ✔️

C — Consistency (Data Always Valid)
Meaning

Database must always stay in a valid state after transaction.

Banking Rules

Balance never negative

Account must exist

Amount must be > 0

Total debit = total credit (in transfer)

Example

Withdraw ₹2000 from account with ₹1000

❌ Should NOT allow → violates consistency
DB must reject.

I — Isolation (No Interference)
Meaning

Multiple transactions should not affect each other incorrectly.

Problem (Race Condition)

Balance = ₹1000

Thread 1 withdraw ₹800 → new = ₹200
Thread 2 withdraw ₹500 → new = -₹300 ❌

Isolation prevents this.
Isolation Levels
Level	Behavior
READ UNCOMMITTED	Dirty reads allowed ❌
READ COMMITTED	Only committed data
REPEATABLE READ	Same row stable
SERIALIZABLE	Fully safe (slow but strongest)

Banking usually uses:
👉 REPEATABLE READ or SERIALIZABLE

D — Durability (Never Lost)
Meaning

Once transaction is committed → data is permanently saved.

Even if:

Server crashes

Power failure

Restart happens

Data must remain.

Achieved using:

WAL (Write Ahead Log)

Disk persistence

DB recovery

🧠 Real Banking Example (Putting All Together)

Transfer ₹5000 A → B

Property	What Happens
Atomicity	Debit + Credit both succeed OR rollback
Consistency	Balance never negative
Isolation	No double withdrawal
Durability	Once success → permanent
