Transactions in Spring Boot (@Transactional) — Deep Dive 🔥
Transactions in Spring Boot (Deep Dive)
1️⃣ What is a Database Transaction?

A transaction = group of DB operations executed as one unit.

Either:

All succeed ✔️

OR all rollback ❌

Banking Example — Money Transfer

Transfer ₹1000 from A → B

Steps:

Deduct from A

Add to B

Insert transaction record

If step 2 fails → step 1 must rollback.

Without transaction → money loss ❌
With transaction → safe ✔️

2️⃣ Spring Boot Support — @Transactional

Spring manages DB transactions automatically.

@Transactional
public void transferMoney(Long from, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
    debit(from, amount);
    credit(to, amount);
}

What Spring Does Internally

Opens DB transaction

Executes all queries

If success → COMMIT

If exception → ROLLBACK

3️⃣ Rollback Behavior
Auto Rollback Happens When:

RuntimeException occurs

Error occurs

@Transactional
public void transfer(...) {
   debit();
   if(true) throw new RuntimeException("Fail");
   credit();
}


Result → debit rolled back ✔️

Checked Exception Case (Important)

By default → NO rollback

@Transactional
public void transfer() throws Exception {
   debit();
   throw new Exception("Fail");
}

Fix
@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)

4️⃣ Transaction Propagation

Controls how transactions behave when calling another method.

REQUIRED (Default)

Join existing OR create new.

@Transactional
public void A() {
   B();  // same transaction
}

REQUIRES_NEW

Always create new transaction.

@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)


Used for:

Audit logs

Independent save

SUPPORTS / MANDATORY / NEVER

Less used — learn later.

5️⃣ Isolation Level (Concurrency Control)
@Transactional(isolation = Isolation.SERIALIZABLE)

Level	Safety	Speed
READ_COMMITTED	Medium	Fast
REPEATABLE_READ	High	Medium
SERIALIZABLE	Highest	Slow

Banking → REPEATABLE_READ / SERIALIZABLE

6️⃣ Read Only Transactions (Performance)
@Transactional(readOnly = true)


Use for:

Fetch queries

Reports

Statements

Improves performance.

7️⃣ Common Mistakes ⚠️
❌ Calling transactional method inside same class

Spring AOP won’t trigger.

this.transfer();  ❌


Must be called via Spring Bean.

❌ Missing @Transactional in transfer logic

→ Causes partial updates

❌ Long-running transactions

→ DB locks, slow system

8️⃣ Real Banking Flow
Transfer Service
 ├── Debit Account
 ├── Credit Account
 ├── Save Transaction
 └── Commit


If ANY fails → rollback everything ✔️

Concurrency & Race Conditions (20 min)
1️⃣ What is Concurrency?

When multiple users/threads access the same data at the same time.

Example:

2 users withdraw money simultaneously

1000 users transfer money at once

2️⃣ What is a Race Condition?

When final result depends on execution order of threads → causes wrong data.

Banking Example (Classic)

Initial Balance = ₹1000

Two withdrawals happen at same time:

Thread-1 → withdraw ₹800
Thread-2 → withdraw ₹500

Without Lock (Problem)
Thread-1 reads balance = 1000
Thread-2 reads balance = 1000

Thread-1 updates → 200
Thread-2 updates → -300 ❌


💥 Balance becomes NEGATIVE → data corruption

3️⃣ Where Race Conditions Occur in Banking?

Withdraw

Transfer

Deposit + Withdraw at same time

Updating same account

Updating same row concurrently

4️⃣ Solutions to Prevent Race Conditions
Solution 1 — Pessimistic Lock (DB Lock)

Lock row until transaction completes.

@Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
Account findById(Long id);


DB prevents other threads from modifying row.

✔ Safe
❌ Slower (waiting)

Used in:
👉 Money transfer, withdraw

Solution 2 — Optimistic Lock (Versioning)

Uses @Version field.

@Version
private Long version;


If another thread updates same row → exception thrown → retry.

✔ Faster
✔ Good for high traffic
❌ Needs retry logic

Solution 3 — SERIALIZABLE Isolation (Strongest)
@Transactional(isolation = Isolation.SERIALIZABLE)


Prevents concurrent anomalies but slow.

Solution 4 — Database Constraint

Prevent negative balance.

CHECK (balance >= 0)


Even if bug happens → DB blocks invalid update.

5️⃣ Real Banking Strategy (Used in Production)

Banks use combination:

Transaction (@Transactional)

Pessimistic Lock (for money ops)

Optimistic Lock (for scale)

Retry mechanism

DB constraints

Audit logs

