📘 CAP Theorem (Distributed Systems Core)

CAP explains trade-offs in distributed databases/systems.

You can guarantee ONLY 2 out of 3:

C → Consistency
A → Availability
P → Partition Tolerance

1️⃣ Consistency (C)

All nodes return same, latest data.

Example:

Balance updated → every server shows updated balance immediately.

Banking requires strong consistency for money safety.

2️⃣ Availability (A)

System always responds — even if some nodes fail.

Example:

Server crash happens → still system responds (maybe stale data).

High availability systems:

Social media

Shopping apps

Search engines

3️⃣ Partition Tolerance (P)

System continues working even when network breaks between nodes.

Example:

Microservices cannot talk due to network issue

DB cluster node disconnected

Still system runs

In distributed systems → Partition always possible → so P is mandatory.

4️⃣ Why Only 2 of 3?

When network partition happens:

If you choose Consistency → must reject requests → Availability lost

If you choose Availability → may return stale data → Consistency lost

So you choose:

CP OR AP (not all 3)

5️⃣ Real Systems Choice
System Type	Choice	Reason
Banking	CP	Correct money > availability
Payment	CP	No wrong balance allowed
Social Media	AP	Availability > perfect consistency
DNS	AP	Must respond always
6️⃣ Banking Example

Account balance = ₹1000

Network partition occurs between DB nodes.

If CP:

System blocks withdrawal until sync → safe ✔️

If AP:

Allows withdrawal on stale node → double spend ❌

Banking must choose CP

